iting the scope of the conflict, holding chemical and biological weapons in reserve, seeking outside support, and leveraging international non-use norms. Avey demonstrates clearly that nuclear weapons cast a definite but limited shadow, and while the world continues to face various nuclear challenges, understanding conflict in nuclear monopoly will remain a pressing concern for analysts and policymakers.Thanks to generous funding from Virginia Tech and its participation in TOME, the ebook editions of this book are available as Open Access volumes, available from Cornell Open (cornellpress.cornell.edu/cornell-open) and other repositories.  afunded by Virginia Tech as part of the TOME initiative  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAsymmetric warfarevCase studies. 0aNo first use (Nuclear strategy)vCase studies. 0aNuclear weaponsxGovernment policyvCase studies. 0aSecurity, InternationalvCase studies. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSecurity Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  anuclear weapons, asymmetric conflict, limited war, Soviet Union, China, Egypt, Iraq, strategy, coercion, international relations.2 aVirginia Tech as part of the TOME initiativeefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2019z9783